output:
1. Infeed System: - Parcel are loaded manually on the 5 + 1(optional) telescopic belt conveyors, 
which are further connected to infeed conveyors of auto-induct lines. These parcels travel 
from lower level to Mezzanine level and goes through aligning conveyors present before the 
auto-induct lines. 
2. Autoinduction lines: - Once the parcels are aligned, they travel further to Auto-induct line. 
Feedlines automatically induct the parcels on the Cross-Belt Sorter Loop 
3. Loop CBS: - Once the parcels are on main loop, the CBS sorts the parcels into respective 
chutes using data from La poste Sorting logic. 
4. Sorting Output: - The sorted shipments are discharged into three types of chutes. 
a. Gravity Chute- there are 58 gravity chutes present in the system with a capacity to 
collect approx. 170 parcels in each chute. 
b. Mini Gravity Chute- There are 70 + 50 (Optional) mini gravity chutes in the system 
with a capacity to collect approx. 100 parcels in each chute. 
c. Bulk Output- One bulk chute is present in the system which further connects to TBC 
for outbound activity. 
d. Rejection Chute- 7 rejection chutes are present to handle the exception parcels. 
e. Strand Chute- One strand chute is planned to handle the parcels as per the 
discussion with LA POSTE team. 
5. Exception refeeding: - Parcel sorted in rejection chute undergo manual correction & again 
fed to CBS via infeed line.

The system consists of 5 infeed lines for Small and Big Parcels. 
• Shipments will get loaded on their respective infeed lines and will move in the volume 
distribution loop (VDS). 
• The operators will pick the shipments from the volume distribution loop and load them on the 
auto-induct lines respectively. 
• The operators will place the shipments on the loading conveyor with barcode facing the 
topside and then the shipments will get buffered and get intelligently merged on the cross
belt sorter loop. 
• Once the shipments are on the cross-belt loop, they will pass through a tunnel where the 
barcodes of the shipments will get scanned from the topside and the volume of the shipments 
will be captured.
Based on the information gathered for barcode and volume scanning, the shipments will get 
sorted in their respective collection’s chute or direct bagging chutes. Bosts to define the 
threshold of volume. 
• The bags which are created at direct bagging chutes will be loaded on the bagging conveyor 
and will be transported to the bagging induct line where the operator will scan the barcodes 
on the bags and the bags will be autoloaded on the sorter. 
• Based on the information captured from the barcode scanning, the bags will get sorted into 
the large shipment chute. The operators standing near the collection chutes will pick the bags, 
scan their barcode once again from their handheld scanner and will place them on their 
respective pallets for dispatch.

1. Infeed System: - Bags containing shipments are unsealed and dumped in bulk onto the infeed 
lines of the Cross belt sorter equipped with Telescopic belt conveyor. The shipments ascend 
to a higher level and arrive at the VDS system. Once the shipments are within the VDS loop, 
they are evenly distributed among all inducts using Arm VDS technology. 
2. Inducts: - After the shipments are collected in the VDS chute, an operator picks and positions 
each shipment on the induct line, ensuring that the shipment is properly aligned and that its 
barcode is facing upwards. The feedlines then automatically induct the shipments onto the 
Cross-Belt Sorter Loop. 
3. Loop CBS: - Once the shipments have entered the main loop, the Cross-Belt Sorter (CBS) 
efficiently sorts the shipments into their respective output chutes by utilizing the data 
provided by Shadowfax's sorting logic. 
4. Output Chutes: - The shipments are discharged into two types of chutes. 
a. Direct Bagging Chutes (L-type) - Within a double decker loop CBS system, there are a 
total of 104 L-Type direct bagging chutes. Shipments collected within these direct 
bagging chutes are bagged & will be treated as high volume chute. 
b. Secondary Chutes (L-type) - Within a double decker loop CBS system, there are a total 
of 100 L-Type Secondary chutes. Shipments collected within these secondary chutes 
Further undergo sortation via PTL setup Placed at two levels. 
c. Rejection Chute- Four rejection chutes are present to handle rejected Shipments. 
5. Put To Light System:- In the system there are 3000 PTL locations. Each secondary chute is 
linked to 30 PTL locations, The PTL racks are placed in L-Shape double decker arrangement. 
6. Bag Takeaway Conveyor: - Following the direct bagging process & secondary sorting process, 
the shipments are placed into bags and then manually loaded onto a bag takeaway conveyor 
located beneath the CBS loop. This conveyor transports the bags out of shipment sorter to 
Outbound sorter located beneath base mezzanine in the approx. centre of the loop CBS.

. Manual Infeed System: - Shipments are placed in singulation on the infeed conveyor lines. 
These shipments are then transported upward via an inclined conveyor to auto induct line. 
2. Infeed from Telescopic Conveyors: Shipments are placed in singulation on the telescopic 
conveyor lines. These shipments are then transported upward via an inclined conveyor to auto 
induct line. 
3. Auto Induct Line: Auto Induct line will induct the parcel automatically on to the sorter. . 
4. Loop CBS: - Once shipments enter the Loop CBS, the Cross-Belt Sorter efficiently sorts them 
into the appropriate output chutes using MONDIAL RELAY's sorting logic. 
5. Scanning & Dimensioning System. In the proposed solution 5 Side scanning and Dimensioning 
system are planned on the Cross Belt Sorter system. 
6. Chutes: - The shipments are discharged into below type of chutes: 
a. Live Dock Chute 
b. Manual Chute  
c. Technical Chute
